<h2 id="wimp-interface">WIMP Interface</h2>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909224524728.png" alt="image-20220909224524728" /></p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>W</strong>indows, <strong>I</strong>cons, Menus, <strong>P</strong>ointers
    <ul>
      <li>default style for majority of interactive computer systems, especially PCs and desktop machines</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909224547069.png" alt="image-20220909224547069" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>Before WIMP: <strong>Command Line Interface (CLI)</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Needed to know each commandâ€™s keyword</li>
      <li>Needed to know the syntax for each comman</li>
      <li>Eg. Copy source_file destination_file</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="problems-with-cli">Problems With CLI</h2>

<ul>
  <li>People found it hard to use
    <ul>
      <li>Forgot command names</li>
      <li>Would transpose command parameters (ì˜µì…˜ì´ ë§ìŒ)</li>
      <li>Novices would be overwhelmed (â€˜blank screenâ€™)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Cognitive analysis</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Many of the problems can be traced to recall vs. recognition memory
        <ul>
          <li>recallë³´ë‹¤ recognitionì´ ë§ì•„ì§€ë„ë¡ êµ¬ì„±</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Commands and syntax had to be recalled (quite hard)</li>
      <li>Almost no recall cues are provided</li>
      <li>Can expect even experts to make mistakes</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="solution-wimp">Solution: WIMP</h2>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909224633098.png" alt="image-20220909224633098" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Xerox invented the Windows Icons Mouse and Pointer (WIMP) interface</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Very few commands (mouse buttons), bring up options</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Visual metaphor</li>
      <li>Contextually appropriate commands are brought up</li>
      <li>Drag &amp; Drop â€˜removesâ€™ parameters</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="why-wimp-works">Why WIMP works</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Uses recognition rather than recall
    <ul>
      <li>Icons show available commands</li>
      <li>Menus give complete list of available commands</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Visual metaphor removes abstract syntax
    <ul>
      <li>No longer remember order of commands or positions in path trees</li>
      <li>Can â€˜seeâ€™ where things are, move them from place to place</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Reduced likelyhood of making syntax errors</li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="windows-icons-pointers">Windows, Icons, Pointers</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Windows: Areas of the screen that behave as if they were independent
    <ul>
      <li>can contain text or graphics</li>
      <li>can be moved or resized or overlapped</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Icons: Small picture or image to represent some object in the interface
    <ul>
      <li>can be many, various, highly stylized, and realistic representations.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Pointers: WIMP style relies on pointing and selecting things
    <ul>
      <li>minimal typing</li>
      <li>wide variety of graphical images</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="and-menus">and Menus</h2>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909224825209.png" alt="image-20220909224825209" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>Set of options displayed on the screen</li>
  <li>Options visible
    <ul>
      <li>less recall - easier to use</li>
      <li>rely on recognition so names should be meaningful</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Selection by:
    <ul>
      <li>numbers, letters, arrow keys, mouse</li>
      <li>combination (e.g. mouse plus accelerators)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Often options hierarchically grouped
    <ul>
      <li>sensible grouping is needed</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>problem â€“ take a lot of screen space solution â€“ pop-up: menu appears when needed</li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="kinds-of-menus">Kinds of Menus</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Menu bar at top of screen, menu drags down
    <ul>
      <li>pull-down menu - mouse hold and drag down menu, and remains available as long as the user holds it open</li>
      <li>drop-down menu - mouse click reveals menu</li>
      <li>fall-down menus - mouse just moves over bar!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Contextual menu appears where you are
    <ul>
      <li>pop-up menus - actions for selected object
        <ul>
          <li>ìš°í´ë¦­</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>pie menus - arranged in a circle
        <ul>
          <li>easier to select item (larger target area)</li>
          <li>Quicker (same distance to any option) â€¦ but not widely used!</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909224925360.png" alt="image-20220909224925360" /></p>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="menus-extras">Menus extras</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Cascading menus
    <ul>
      <li>hierarchical menu structure</li>
      <li>menu selection opens new menu</li>
      <li>and so in ad infinitum</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Keyboard accelerators
    <ul>
      <li>key combinations - same effect as menu item</li>
      <li>two kinds
        <ul>
          <li>active when menu open â€“ usually first letter</li>
          <li>active when menu closed â€“ usually Ctrl + letter</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>usually different with different applications!!!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="3-menus-design-issues-buttons--dialogue-boxes">3. Menus design issues: Buttons &amp; Dialogue boxes</h2>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909225053446.png" alt="image-20220909225053446" /></p>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909225102566.png" alt="image-20220909225102566" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>individual and isolated regions within a display that can be selected to invoke an action</li>
  <li>Special kinds</li>
  <li>radio buttons
    <ul>
      <li>set of mutually exclusive choices</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>check boxes
    <ul>
      <li>set of non-exclusive choices</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Dialogue boxes (ê·¸ë¦¼ 4)
    <ul>
      <li>information windows that pop up to inform of an important event or request information.</li>
      <li>e.g: when saving a file, a dialogue box is displayed to get the filename and location. Once the file is saved, the box disappears.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="toolbars">Toolbars</h2>

<p><img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/speardragon/save-image-repo/main/img/image-20220909225154429.png" alt="image-20220909225154429" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>long lines of icons â€¦ â€¦ but what do they do?
    <ul>
      <li>fast access to common actions</li>
      <li>often customizable:
        <ul>
          <li>choose which toolbars to see</li>
          <li>choose what options are on it</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Palettes and tear-off menus</li>
  <li>Problem: menu not there when you want it</li>
  <li>Solution:
    <ul>
      <li>palettes â€“ little windows of actions, shown/hidden via menu option. e.g. available shapes in drawing package tear-off and pin-up menus â€“ menu â€˜tears offâ€™ to become palette</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>

<h2 id="look-and--feel">Look and â€¦ feel</h2>

<ul>
  <li>WIMP systems have the same elements:
    <ul>
      <li>windows, icons., menus, pointers, buttons, etc.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>but different window systems â€¦ behave differently
    <ul>
      <li>e.g. MacOS vs Windows menus</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>appearance + behaviour = look and feel
    <ul>
      <li>easy to focus on look</li>
      <li>what about feel?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

